&lt;p&gt;Padua, a city in close proximity to the Queen of the Adriatic, Venice, appears to live in the shadow of its more &amp;#8220;popular&amp;#8221; neighbor.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;During our weekend escape to Padua, we discovered a charming cityÂ thatÂ boasts of a renowned university (dating back to 1222) whose alumni and professors list includes Galileo Galilei, CopernicusÂ andÂ William Harvey. The world&amp;#8217;s first university &lt;a title=&#34;Botanical Garden, Padua&#34; href=&#34;http://www.ortobotanico.unipd.it/en/&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;botanical garden&lt;/a&gt; finds its home here, and features in the UNESCO heritage list. Many pilgrims visit the beautiful &lt;a title=&#34;Basilica of St. Anthony&#34; href=&#34;http://www.basilicadelsanto.org/ing/home.asp&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;basilica of St. Anthony of Padua&lt;/a&gt;. A large part of Shakespeare&amp;#8217;s Taming of the Shrew is based in this city.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here&amp;#8217;s what we loved aboutÂ Padua:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;B&amp;#8217;s favorite pick would, most certainly,Â beÂ the &lt;a title=&#34;Basilica of St. Anthony of Padua&#34; href=&#34;http://www.basilicadelsanto.org/ing/home.asp&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;basilicaÂ of St. AnthonyÂ of Padua&lt;/a&gt;, also known as Il Santo.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We walked through porticoes in the streetsÂ to reach the shrine and admire its tranquil interior. The cupolas of this basilica adorn the skyline of Padua and make for beautiful postcard images.Â The statue of a horse and its rider in the square outside is one of Donatello&amp;#8217;s creations.&lt;/p&gt;

